ut information that I have or have not provided. Even if you just want to say hello to someone, I am always wired in!\r\n\r\n--Pierce','A Little About Me','','inherit','open','open','','32-revision-17','','','2011-02-12 00:35:49','2011-02-12 06:35:49','',32,'http://nerdtraining.info/2011/02/12/32-revision-17/',0,'revision','',0),(70,1,'2011-02-19 17:52:49','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Hey there guys. Today we\'re going to go over a few really cool things that I have been working on and learning over the last few days.\n\n<h2>Inception</h2>\nSeveral days ago, I became completely fed up with Google Chrome\'s utterly horrifying default \"new tab\" page. I know that installing a new theme resolves this problem, but I wanted to do something unique as almost all the themes I saw were overly colored and just not my cup of tea. I set to work on creating a new page that I would set as my new tab page. After about 30 minutes, I had this:\n\n<<!!-- INSERT SCREENSHOT OF BROWSER WITH LONG URL --!!>>\n\nDefinitely a great start, but still a work in progress. The ideas started flowing freely. So much possibility! There was one major problem though:\n\n<h2>Accessibility</h2>\n\nI have a system in place that allows me to get around the web browser quickly: <code>ctrl + T</code> to open a new tab, then start typing. Chrome\'s \"Omnibox\" takes care of the rest. Now take a look at that picture again. See what\'s wrong? The address bar has an enormously massive file URL inside it. Whenever I opened a new tab and started typing, it would just append my text to the end of that incredibly long URL, which led to me having to double- or triple-click the address bar and press the <code>delete</code> key so that I could get started on my hunt for the interwebs. \n\n<h2>Solution?</h2>\n\nI quickly downloaded a \"change your new tab page\" extension in the hopes that my problem would be eviscerated and I could just point it at my custom file. The result? What you see above in that picture. Yes, indeed. All the new tab changer extension did was to type in the address to the file and send me there. NOT a help.\n\n<h2>Eureka!</h2>\n\nAt this point, many people would have just turned away and accepted defeat with that ugly brown default new tab. Me? No. I decided enough was enough and that to really stick it to the man, I had to go the extra mile and write my own browser extension. The end result? This.\n\n<<!!-- INSERT PICTURE OF NEW TAB PAGE WITH EXTENSION --!!>>\n\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n\nOver the course of a few posts to come after this, I will teach you all about how I put this extension together from start to finish, as well as talk about the roadmap for this extension\'s future. Hint: The future\'s bright, go buy yourself a pair of sunglasses.\n\nUntil next time, peeps. Adios!','Beginner\'s Luck: How I Started Writing my First Google Chrome Extension','','draft','open','open','','','','','2011-02-19 17:52:49','2011-02-19 23:52:49','',0,'http://nerdtraining.info/?p=70',0,'post','',0),(53,1,'2011-02-12 04:45:45','2011-02-12 10:45:45','I am sure that someday I will write a more exhaustive article weighing the pros and cons of making the switch to solid state drives (SSDs), but today I just wanted to share a comparison of the two, having recently made the jump myself.\r\n\r\nThe original hard drive running my Windows installation was a 500gb Western Digital green drive, running 5400rpm and spinning to 7200rpm whenever data was required. \r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_56\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"345\" caption=\"Western Digital 500gb Green Drive\"]<a href=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/wd500gbDrive.jpg\"><img src=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/wd500gbDrive.jpg\" alt=\"Western Digital 500gb Green Drive\" title=\"Western Digital 500gb Green Drive\" width=\"345\" height=\"345\" class=\"size-full wp-image-56\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe new setup that I just got installed includes two 60gb OC Z Agility 2 solid state drives and a 4 port Syba RAID controller (mucho cheapo, to be honest).\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_54\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"450\" caption=\"OCZ Agility 2 2.5-inch SSD\"]<a href=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/OCZ-Agility-2-MLC-2.5-inch-SSD.jpg\"><img src=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/OCZ-Agility-2-MLC-2.5-inch-SSD.jpg\" alt=\"OCZ Agility 2 2.5-inch SSD\" title=\"OCZ Agility 2 2.5-inch SSD\" width=\"450\" height=\"340\" class=\"size-full wp-image-54\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_55\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"616\" caption=\"Syba 4 Port RAID Controller\"]<a href=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/sybaRaidController.jpg\"><img src=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/sybaRaidController.jpg\" alt=\"Syba 4 Port RAID Controller\" title=\"Syba 4 Port RAID Controller\" width=\"616\" height=\"436\" class=\"size-full wp-image-55\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nJust for a bit of foundation, the rest of the computer includes an Intel Core2Quad 6600 Processor running 2.4ghz on a Gigabyte motherboard with 4gb of G.Skill RAM.\r\n\r\n<h2>The Fun Stuff</h2>\r\n\r\nI just took the time to measure the speed of the normal HDD using <a href=\"http://www.hdtune.com/\">HDTune</a>, a hard disk benchmarking application. These were my results:\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_57\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"570\" caption=\"WD500gb Hard Drive Benchmark\"]<a href=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/HDTune_Benchmark_WDC_WD5000AACS-00ZUB0.png\"><img src=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/HDTune_Benchmark_WDC_WD5000AACS-00ZUB0.png\" alt=\"WD500gb Hard Drive Benchmark\" title=\"WD500gb Hard Drive Benchmark\" width=\"570\" height=\"460\" class=\"size-full wp-image-57\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nNot horrible, but pretty much exactly what we have come to expect from a platter-based hard drive. Definitely not good, just acceptable. What we have come to expect.\r\n<h3>Pertinent Data from HDD Test</a></h3>\r\nAverage Read Rate: 60mb/s (Not too shabby)\r\nAverage Seek/Access time: 14ms (Shabby)\r\nObservation: As strain is continuously placed on the hard drive, the read rates drop and the access times go up. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nNow, let\'s take a look at how nice dual SSDs in RAID 0 changed the game:\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_58\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"570\" caption=\"120gb Dual SSD RAID 0 Benchmark\"]<a href=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/HDTune_Benchmark_LovestickSr.png\"><img src=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/HDTune_Benchmark_LovestickSr.png\" alt=\"120gb Dual SSD RAID 0 Benchmark\" title=\"120gb Dual SSD RAID 0 Benchmark\" width=\"570\" height=\"460\" class=\"size-full wp-image-58\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nWow. I know right? It\'s okay, you don\'t need to say anything.\r\n\r\n<h3>Pertinent Data from SSD Test</h3>\r\nAverage Read Rate: 154.4mb/s\r\nAccess Times: <strong>0.2ms</strong> (Yes, you read that correctly. 0.2ms!)\r\nObservation: Even during extended strain on the disk, the disk\'s read rate never drops more than 1mb/s total, in fact gets even faster as time goes on.\r\n\r\n<h2>What This Means</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>As tested, the Dual SSD RAID 0 setup increased disk read rate by almost 3 times.</li>\r\n	<li>As tested, the setup decreased data access times to <strong>1/73</strong> of their original values.</li>\r\n	<li>Solid state technology does not suffer from the negative effects of moving parts, and consequently is not affected by extended strain.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\r\nThere\'s really not any other way to say it: SSD is the way to go. And if you have $300? Get two and throw \'em in a RAID controller. Who knows? If you spend more than $30 on a RAID controller, you could likely increase your disk read rate to as much as 400mb/s. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\nThat\'s all for now. Y\'all take it easy!\r\n-Pierce','The Benefits of SSDs over Normal HDDs','','publish','open','open','','the-benefits-of-ssds-over-normal-hdds','','','2011-02-12 14:07:12','2011-02-12 20:07:12','',0,'http://nerdtraining.info/?p=53',0,'post','',1),(54,1,'2011-02-12 04:02:42','2011-02-12 10:02:42','','OCZ Agility 2 2.5-inch SSD','OCZ Agility 2 2.5-inch SSD','inherit','open','open','','ocz-agility-2-mlc-2-5-inch-ssd','','','2011-02-12 04:02:42','2011-02-12 10:02:42','',53,'http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/OCZ-Agility-2-MLC-2.5-inch-SSD.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(55,1,'2011-02-12 04:02:44','2011-02-12 10:02:44','','Syba 4 Port RAID Controller','Syba 4 Port RAID Controller','inherit','open','open','','sybaraidcontroller','','','2011-02-12 04:02:44','2011-02-12 10:02:44','',53,'http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/sybaRaidController.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(56,1,'2011-02-12 04:02:45','2011-02-12 10:02:45','','Western Digital 500gb Green Drive','Western Digital 500gb Green Drive','inherit','open','open','','wd500gbdrive','','','2011-02-12 04:02:45','2011-02-12 10:02:45','',53,'http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/wd500gbDrive.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(57,1,'2011-02-12 04:16:07','2011-02-12 10:16:07','','WD500gb Hard Drive Benchmark','WD500gb Hard Drive Benchmark','inherit','open','open','','hdtune_benchmark_wdc_wd5000aacs-00zub0','','','2011-02-12 04:16:07','2011-02-12 10:16:07','',53,'http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/HDTune_Benchmark_WDC_WD5000AACS-00ZUB0.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(58,1,'2011-02-12 04:16:12','2011-02-12 10:16:12','','120gb Dual SSD RAID 0 Benchmark','120gb Dual SSD RAID 0 Benchmark','inherit','open','open','','hdtune_benchmark_lovesticksr','','','2011-02-12 04:16:12','2011-02-12 10:16:12','',53,'http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/HDTune_Benchmark_LovestickSr.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(59,1,'2011-02-12 04:13:41','2011-02-12 10:13:41','I am sure that someday I will write a more e