s to <strong>1/73</strong> of their original values.</li>\r\n	<li>Solid state technology does not suffer from the negative effects of moving parts, and consequently is not affected by extended strain.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\r\nThere\'s really not any other way to say it: SSD is the way to go. And if you have $300? Get two and throw \'em in a RAID controller. Who knows? If you spend more than $30 on a RAID controller, you could likely increase your disk read rate to as much as 400mb/s. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\nThat\'s all for now. Y\'all take it easy!\r\n-Pierce','The Benefits of SSDs over Normal HDDs','','inherit','open','open','','53-revision-9','','','2011-02-12 04:45:17','2011-02-12 10:45:17','',53,'http://nerdtraining.info/2011/02/12/53-revision-9/',0,'revision','',0),(68,1,'2011-02-12 04:45:45','2011-02-12 10:45:45','I am sure that someday I will write a more exhaustive article weighing the pros and cons of making the switch to solid state drives (SSDs), but today I just wanted to share a comparison of the two, having recently made the jump myself.\r\n\r\nThe original hard drive running my Windows installation was a 500gb Western Digital green drive, running 5400rpm and spinning to 7200rpm whenever data was required. \r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_56\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"345\" caption=\"Western Digital 500gb Green Drive\"]<a href=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/wd500gbDrive.jpg\"><img src=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/wd500gbDrive.jpg\" alt=\"Western Digital 500gb Green Drive\" title=\"Western Digital 500gb Green Drive\" width=\"345\" height=\"345\" class=\"size-full wp-image-56\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe new setup that I just got installed includes two 60gb OC Z Agility 2 solid state drives and a 4 port Syba RAID controller (mucho cheapo, to be honest).\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_54\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"450\" caption=\"OCZ Agility 2 2.5-inch SSD\"]<a href=\"http://ne