 the read rates drop and the access times go up. \r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nNow, let\'s take a look at how nice dual SSDs in RAID 0 changed the game:\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_58\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"570\" caption=\"120gb Dual SSD RAID 0 Benchmark\"]<a href=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/HDTune_Benchmark_LovestickSr.png\"><img src=\"http://nerdtraining.info/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/HDTune_Benchmark_LovestickSr.png\" alt=\"120gb Dual SSD RAID 0 Benchmark\" title=\"120gb Dual SSD RAID 0 Benchmark\" width=\"570\" height=\"460\" class=\"size-full wp-image-58\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nWow. I know right? It\'s okay, you don\'t need to say anything.\r\n\r\n<h3>Pertinent Data from SSD Test</h3>\r\nAverage Read Rate: 154.4mb/s\r\nAccess Times: <strong>0.2ms</strong> (Yes, you read that correctly. 0.2ms!)\r\nObservation: Even during extended strain on the disk, the disk\'s read rate never drops more than 1mb/s total, in fact gets even faster as time goes on.\r\n\r\n<h2>What This Means</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>As tested, the Dual SSD RAID 0 setup increased disk read rate by almost 3 times.</li>\r\n	<li>As tested, the setup decreased data access times to <strong>1/73</strong> of their original values.</li>\r\n	<li>Solid state technology does not suffer from the negative effects of moving parts, and consequently is not affected by extended strain.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\r\nThere\'s really not any other way to say it: SSD is the way to go. And if you have $300? Get two and throw \'em in a RAID controller. Who knows? If you spend more than $30 on a RAID controller, you could likely increase your disk read rate to as much as 400mb/s. \r\n\r\n<br /><br />\r\nThat\'s all for now. Y\'all take it easy!\r\n-Pierce','The Benefits of SSDs over Normal HDDs','','inherit','open','open','','53-revision-10','','','2011-02-12 04:45:45','2011-02-12 10:45:45','',53,'http://nerdtraining.info/2011/02/12/53-revision-10/',0,'revision','',0),(69,1,'2011-0