,'open','open','','70-revision-3','','','2011-02-19 17:43:42','2011-02-19 23:43:42','',70,'http://nerdtraining.info/2011/02/19/70-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(74,1,'2011-02-19 18:30:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Hello feeps, tweeps, and peeps. Today\'s topic is a really exciting one: Google Chrome extension building. The process for building a simple or even moderately complex extension is actually incredibly easy, and with a little bit of work you can have your very own extension up and running and even online in the Google Chrome extension market in just a few hours!\r\n\r\n<h2>Getting Started: The Idea</h2>\r\n\r\nEvery extension is based on an idea: What the hell am I going to write an extension about? Good question, Jack! And one that I can\'t answer, unfortunately. I did, however, have my own idea of <a href=\"#\">writing a new tab extension of my very own</a> called \"Bad Ass New Tab Page\" to replace the gross, brown, horrible default Chrome new tab page. I\'m going to use this idea and extension over the next few tutorial posts in this series in order to show virtually all the important aspects and necessary skills to writing a fully-featured Google Chrome extension. And with that, let\'s get started building the \"Bad Ass New Tab Page\" extension for Chrome!\r\n\r\n<h2>Lights, Camera, Action!</h2>\r\n\r\nFirst things first, grab yourself a coffee and a bottle of water, this is going to be a fun ride. Let\'s start with creating a folder on your computer, wherever you want (mine is in my <a href=\"http://www.dropbox.com\">dropbox</a>), called \"BANTP\". In this folder, you are going to create a few files, the only files really required in order to create an extension:<br />\r\n[php]index.html\r\nmanifest.json[/php]\r\n1) Index.html is the main view of your extension, because without a view there is no extension.\r\n2) Manifest.json is the heart and soul of the extension, and absolutely imperative to be correct. Without a correct <code>manifest.json</code>, your extension most likely will not even install correctly but certainly won\'t perform the way you want it to.\r\n\r\nThese two files are all we need to get started, but rest assured that we will be adding many more files and folders very quickly.\r\n\r\n<h2>Let the coding begin</h2>\r\n\r\nThis is where things get fun. We are going to get just enough code into each of these files so that we can have a working new tab page as quickly as possible. Go ahead and open up index.html, and let\'s get a dinky little something to show up as a web page.\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n&lt;html&gt;\r\n      &lt;head&gt;\r\n            &lt;title&gt;New Tab Working!&lt;/title&gt;\r\n      &lt;/head&gt;\r\n      &lt;body&gt;\r\n            &lt;h2&gt;This is a new tab page, and it is working! Awesome, possum!&lt;/h2&gt;\r\n      &lt;/body&gt;\r\n&lt;/html&gt;\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\nWe\'re keeping it simple. <strong>really</strong> simple. Now, let\'s get into manifest.json. We will go over JSON a little later on, but for now a rough explanation will have to suffice. JSON (Javascript Object Notation) is essentially a way to create, store, and transmit large arrays of information very efficiently using only Javascript.','Writing Your First Google Chrome Extension','','draft','open','open','','','','','2011-02-19 18:30:02','2011-02-20 00:30:02','',0,'http://nerdtraining.info/?p=74',0,'post','',0),(75,1,'2011-02-19 18:00:42','2011-02-20 00:00:42','Hello feeps, tweeps, and peeps. Today\'s topic is a really exciting one: Google Chrome extension building. The process for building a simple or even moderately complex extension is actually incredibly easy, and with a little bit of work you can have your very own extension up and running and even online in the Google Chrome extension market in just a few hours!\n\n<h2>Getting Started: The Idea</h2>\n\nEvery extension is based on an idea: What the hell am I going to write an extension about? Good question, Jack! And one that I can\'t answer, unfortunately. I did,