 make this happen:\r\n<pre>nano hooks/post-receive\r\n[php]\r\n#!/bin/sh\r\nGIT_WORK_TREE=/path/to/our/application git checkout -f master\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\n This should all go well, and you are ALL DONE on the remote server.\r\n<h2>Step Six: Install Git on your LOCAL Computer</h2>\r\nThis is a pretty easy step as well. Even easier for Mac and Linux users. I\'m not going to go step by step, but follow the instructions in the linked tutorials.  For Windows users: <a href=\"http://help.github.com/win-set-up-git/\">http://help.github.com/win-set-up-git/</a> For Mac Users: <a href=\"http://help.github.com/mac-set-up-git/\">http://help.github.com/mac-set-up-git/</a> For Linux Users: <a href=\"http://help.github.com/linux-set-up-git/\">http://help.github.com/linux-set-up-git/</a>\r\n<h2>Step Seven: Get Your Files Ready on Your LOCAL Computer</h2>\r\nFor Windows users, you will need to open \"Git Bash\", which should be available in Start &gt; Programs. Mac and Linux users should already have the Git commands available to them in the command line or terminal.  Navigate to the folder where you are keeping your web application or where you will be keeping the documents. If I were to keep them on my desktop in a folder called \"WebApp\", the command would be (on Windows):\r\n<pre>cd C:/Users/Pierce/Desktop/WebApp/</pre>\r\nNow, we need to initialize the git repository in this folder. This is done so that the filesystem can track changes to the files and update the remote server accordingly.\r\n<pre>git init</pre>\r\nYou should get the following success message:\r\n<pre>Initialized empty git repository...</pre>\r\nNow we need to add the remote server as a git repo and get them communicating.\r\n<pre>git remote add web ssh://git@127.0.0.1/home/git/webapp.git</pre>\r\nIf you are running SSH on a different port than the standard port 22 (recommended) the command becomes\r\n<pre>git remote add web ssh://git@127.0.0.1:1234/home/git/webapp.git</pre>\r\n<h2>Step Eight: Configure the Server to Auto-Checkout Application Files</h2>\r\nNow that we have\r\n\r\nNow, let\'s get our files pushed to the server!\r\n<h2>Step Nine, final step! Push your web application to the server!</h2>\r\n</pre>','Set Up and Maintain a Production Web Application Using Git','','inherit','open','open','','27-revision-21','','','2012-02-03 09:15:36','2012-02-03 15:15:36','',27,'http://piercemoore.com/blog/2012/02/03/27-revision-21/',0,'revision','',0),(49,1,'2012-02-03 09:15:39','2012-02-03 15:15:39','<h1>Why you\'re here:</h1>\r\nToday is a cool day because you\'re going to learn how to set up a web server to run an application using a secure versioning system, Git. Chances are that if you are here you are not a Git master (neither am I) and you need a \"from the tippy top\" instructional manual to guide you from start to finish. No problem! I\'m here to save the day.\r\n<h1>Disclaimer:</h1>\r\nThe tutorial you are about to read is applicable to the set up I have on my current web server, which is running CentOS 5.7. Debian, Fedora, and Ubuntu distros will require different shell commands.\r\n<h1>What you will need:</h1>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>A dedicated server running CentOS or VPS with root shell access (For the purposes of this tutorial, we will not cover a shared hosting environment, sorry)</li>\r\n	<li>A local computer with internet access (duh)</li>\r\n	<li>A basic working knowledge of shell commands and git commands. If not, it\'s okay. We\'ll get through it.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h1>Let\'s get started!</h1>\r\n<h2>Step One:</h2>\r\nEnsure that you have set up your webserver to run Apache, PHP, and MySQL. A tutorial for this will be written shortly.\r\n<h2>Step Two:</h2>\r\nWe will need the EPEL libraries for Yum provided by the CentOS community in order to install Git. SSH into your server using a program like <a title=\"Putty\" href=\"http://www.putty.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Putty</a> and login to the root user. We will install the RPM for EPEL now. These instructions are t