download.fedora.redhat.com/pub/epel/5/x86_64/epel-release-5-4.noarch.rpm</pre>\r\nFor i386 or i686:\r\n<pre>rpm -Uvh http://download.fedora.redhat.com/pub/epel/5/i386/epel-release-5-4.noarch.rpm</pre>\r\nThat should return successfully. If not, start Googling. This article won\'t be covering troubleshooting.Now run the following commands to make sure we have got it right:\r\n<pre>yum update\r\nyum repolist</pre>\r\nYou should see a list of all the yum repos installed on your system, with the new EPEL library installed in the middle. Now, we need to prioritize that repo a little higher. Using your preferred server-side code editor (I prefer Nano, but the industry default is Vim), we need to create a new EPEL.repo file in the yum repo depository:\r\n\r\n<code>nano /etc/yum.repos.d/epel.repo</code>\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n[epel]\r\nname=Extra Packages for Enterprise Linux 5  $basearch\r\n#baseurl=http://download.fedoraproject.org/pub/epel/5/$basearch mirrorlist=http://mirrors.fedoraproject.org/mirrorlist?repo=epel-5&amp;amp;arch=$basearch failovermethod=priority\r\nenabled=1\r\ngpgcheck=1\r\ngpgkey=file:///etc/pki/rpm-gpg/RPM-GPG-KEY-EPEL\r\n\r\n[epel-debuginfo]\r\nname=Extra Packages for Enterprise Linux 5  $basearch  Debug #baseurl=http://download.fedoraproject.org/pub/epel/5/$basearch/debug mirrorlist=http://mirrors.fedoraproject.org/mirrorlist?repo=epel-debug-5&amp;amp;arch=$basearch\r\nfailovermethod=priority\r\nenabled=0\r\ngpgkey=file:///etc/pki/rpm-gpg/RPM-GPG-KEY-EPEL\r\ngpgcheck=1\r\n\r\n[epel-source]\r\nname=Extra Packages for Enterprise Linux 5  $basearch  Source #baseurl=http://download.fedoraproject.org/pub/epel/5/SRPMS mirrorlist=http://mirrors.fedoraproject.org/mirrorlist?repo=epel-source-5&amp;amp;arch=$basearch\r\nfailovermethod=priority\r\nenabled=0\r\ngpgkey=file:///etc/pki/rpm-gpg/RPM-GPG-KEY-EPEL gpgcheck=1\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\nThat should have everything up to date! Now, we install Git.\r\n<h2>Step Three: Install Git on the Remote Server</h2>\r\nThis is actually a really, really easy step. We just need to talk to yum and make it install a few things from EPEL.\r\n<pre>yum install git-all</pre>\r\nThis will get you set up with all the different libraries in Git and enable full functionality. It\'s that easy! Now, let\'s get Git set up on our LOCAL computer.\r\n<h2>Step Four: Create a Git User on the Remote Server</h2>\r\nNow we need to get the Git repo going on the remote server so that our local machine can push files to it. First, let\'s create a Git user on the Remote Server.\r\n<pre>adduser git\r\npasswd git</pre>\r\nMake sure that the password for the remote Git user is a secure one, unless you want to deal with keys (the preferred way to go). Keys are tricky to set up and manage, and we will write a tutorial about that one day. Now, with the git user created, we need to create a repo and set up Git under their username.\r\n<h2>Step Five: Log In to the Remote Server under the Git User and Make Magic</h2>\r\nOpen a new SSH session to the server (you can keep the root session open if you like), and log in with the Git user. Simple.\r\n\r\nNow, we need to navigate to the place where you will be keeping your remote Git repos. I recommend keeping them in the /home/ directory, perhaps in a separate \"repos\" directory \"/home/git/\".\r\n\r\nCreate the new repo and initialize it with the following commands:\r\n<pre>mkdir webapp.git\r\ncd !$\r\ngit init --bare</pre>\r\nNow we need to do one last bit of magic, and this is really the crucial piece of work that makes it all happen. We need to set up our git repo so that it checks out our files to the actual Document Root of the web application whenever it receives a push from a programmer. Run the following commands so that we can make this happen:\r\n<pre>nano hooks/post-receive</pre>\r\nThen, in hooks/post-receive, enter this information. Make sure you change the work tree path to whatever the document root is for your application ( /var/www/html/ ).\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n#!/bin/sh\r\nGIT_WORK_TREE=/path/to/our/application git checkout -f master\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\nThis should all go well, and you are ALL DONE on the remote server.\r\n<h2>Step Six: Install Git on your LOCAL Computer</h2>\r\nThis is a pretty easy step as well. Even easier for Mac and Linux users. I\'m not going to go step by step, but follow the instructions in the linked tutorials.\r\n\r\nFor Windows users: <a href=\"http://help.github.com/win-set-up-git/\">http://help.github.com/win-set-up-git/</a>\r\n\r\nFor Mac Users: <a href=\"http://help.github.com/mac-set-up-git/\">http://help.github.com/mac-set-up-git/</a>\r\n\r\nFor Linux Users: <a href=\"http://help.github.com/linux-set-up-git/\">http://help.github.com/linux-set-up-git/</a>\r\n<h2>Step Seven: Get Your Files Ready on Your LOCAL Computer</h2>\r\nFor Windows users, you will need to open \"Git Bash\", which should be available in Start &gt; Programs. Mac and Linux users should already have the Git commands available to them in the command line or terminal.  Navigate to the folder where you are keeping your web application or where you will be keeping the documents. If I were to keep them on my desktop in a folder called \"WebApp\", the command would be (on Windows):\r\n<pre>cd C:/Users/Pierce/Desktop/WebApp/</pre>\r\nNow, we need to initialize the git repository in this folder. This is done so that the filesystem can track changes to the files and update the remote server accordingly.\r\n<pre>git init</pre>\r\nYou should get the following success message:\r\n<pre>Initialized empty git repository...</pre>\r\nNow we need to add the remote server as a git repo and get them communicating.\r\n<pre>git remote add web ssh://git@127.0.0.1/home/git/webapp.git</pre>\r\nIf you are running SSH on a different port than the standard port 22 (recommended) the command becomes\r\n<pre>git remote add web ssh://git@127.0.0.1:1234/home/git/webapp.git</pre>\r\nNow, let\'s get our files pushed to the server!\r\n<h2>Step Eight, final step! Push your web application to the server!</h2>\r\nMake sure we\'re still in the local directory that will be the working directory for git. At this point, I\'m assuming that you already have the files for your website in the directory so we are just going to send them all to the web server.\r\n<pre>git add *\r\ngit commit -m \"First commit\"\r\ngit push webapp -all</pre>\r\nAnd bam. There it is. With the success of that push (it should work), you should check your remote server in that directory and you should have all your files in it!\r\n<h1>Recap: What we just did and why.</h1>\r\nWe just set up your webserver and local computer with Git, a powerful versioning system. Now you can live without fear of programming. All you need to do now is work on your code locally (which is faster anyway) and push it to the remote server whenever you are done. If it messes something up? You can just revert to a prior commit! That is the power of Git: endless confidence in yourself, your programming, and the stability of your web application.\r\n\r\nHappy Gitting!\r\n\r\n-Pierce','Set Up and Maintain a Production Web Application Using Git','','inherit','open','open','','27-revision-34','','','2012-02-03 09:31:08','2012-02-03 15:31:08','',27,'http://piercemoore.com/blog/2012/02/03/27-revision-34/',0,'revision','',0),(62,1,'2012-02-03 09:31:58','2012-02-03 15:31:58','<h1>Why you\'re here:</h1>\r\nToday is a cool day because you\'re going to learn how to set up a web server to run an application using a secure versioning system, Git. Chances are that if you are here you are not a Git master (neither am I) and you need a \"from the tippy top\" instructional manual to guide you from start to finish. No problem! I\'m here to save the day.\r\n<h1>Disclaimer:</h1>\r\nThe tutorial you are about to read is applicable to the set up I have on my current web server, which is running CentOS 5.7. Debian, Fedora, and Ubuntu distros will require different shell commands.\r\n<h1>What you will need:</h1>