,'How to Run a Production Website with Git','','inherit','open','open','','85-revision','','','2012-02-03 06:41:26','2012-02-03 12:41:26','',85,'http://piercemoore.com/blog/2012/02/03/85-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(70,1,'2011-02-19 17:52:49','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Hey there guys. Today we\'re going to go over a few really cool things that I have been working on and learning over the last few days.\n\n<h2>Inception</h2>\nSeveral days ago, I became completely fed up with Google Chrome\'s utterly horrifying default \"new tab\" page. I know that installing a new theme resolves this problem, but I wanted to do something unique as almost all the themes I saw were overly colored and just not my cup of tea. I set to work on creating a new page that I would set as my new tab page. After about 30 minutes, I had this:\n\n<<!!-- INSERT SCREENSHOT OF BROWSER WITH LONG URL --!!>>\n\nDefinitely a great start, but still a work in progress. The ideas started flowing freely. So much possibility! There was one major problem though:\n\n<h2>Accessibility</h2>\n\nI have a system in place that allows me to get around the web browser quickly: <code>ctrl + T</code> to open a new tab, then start typing. Chrome\'s \"Omnibox\" takes care of the rest. Now take a look at that picture again. See what\'s wrong? The address bar has an enormously massive file URL inside it. Whenever I opened a new tab and started typing, it would just append my text to the end of that incredibly long URL, which led to me having to double- or triple-click the address bar and press the <code>delete</code> key so that I could get started on my hunt for the interwebs.\n\n<h2>Solution?</h2>\n\nI quickly downloaded a \"change your new tab page\" extension in the hopes that my problem would be eviscerated and I could just point it at my custom file. The result? What you see above in that picture. Yes, indeed. All the new tab changer extension did was to type in the address to the file and send me there. NOT a help.\n\n<h2>Eureka!</h2>\n\nAt this point, many people would have just turned away and accepted defeat with that ugly brown default new tab. Me? No. I decided enough was enough and that to really stick it to the man, I had to go the extra mile and write my own browser extension. The end result? This.\n\n<<!!-- INSERT PICTURE OF NEW TAB PAGE WITH EXTENSION --!!>>\n\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n\nOver the course of a few posts to come after this, I will teach you all about how I put this extension together from start to finish, as well as talk about the roadmap for this extension\'s future. Hint: The future\'s bright, go buy yourself a pair of sunglasses.\n\nUntil next time, peeps. Adios!','Beginner&#039;s Luck: How I Started Writing my First Google Chrome Extension','','draft','open','open','','','','','2011-02-19 17:52:49','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://nerdtraining.info/?p=70',0,'post','',0),(74,1,'2011-02-19 18:30:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Hello feeps, tweeps, and peeps. Today\'s topic is a really exciting one: Google Chrome extension building. The process for building a simple or even moderately complex extension is actually incredibly easy, and with a little bit of work you can have your very own extension up and running and even online in the Google Chrome extension market in just a few hours!\n\n<h2>Getting Started: The Idea</h2>\n\nEvery extension is based on an idea: What the hell am I going to write an extension about? Good question, Jack! And one that I can\'t answer, unfortunately. I did, however, have my own idea of <a href=\"#\">writing a new tab extension of my very own</a> called \"Bad Ass New Tab Page\" to replace the gross, brown, horrible default Chrome new tab page. I\'m going to use this idea and extension over the next few tutorial posts in this series in order to show virtually all the important aspects and necessary skills to writing a fully-featured Google Chrome extension. And with that, let\'s get started building the \"Bad Ass New Tab Page\" extension for Chrome!\n\n<h2>Lights, Camera, Action!</h2>\n\nFirst things first, grab yourself a coffee and a bottle of water, this is going to be a fun ride. Let\'s start with creating a folder on your computer, wherever you want (mine is in my <a href=\"http://www.dropbox.com\">dropbox</a>), called \"BANTP\". In this folder, you are going to create a few files, the only files really required in order to create an extension:<br />\n[php]index.html\nmanifest.json[/php]\n1) Index.html is the main view of your extension, because without a view there is no extension.\n2) Manifest.json is the heart and soul of the extension, and absolutely imperative to be correct. Without a correct <code>manifest.json</code>, your extension most likely will not even install correctly but certainly won\'t perform the way you want it to.\n\nThese two files are all we need to get started, but rest assured that we will be adding many more files and folders very quickly.\n\n<h2>Let the coding begin</h2>\n\nThis is where things get fun. We are going to get just enough code into each of these files so that we can have a working new tab page as quickly as possible. Go ahead and open up index.html, and let\'s get a dinky little something to show up as a web page.\n\n[php]\n&lt;html&gt;\n      &lt;head&gt;\n            &lt;title&gt;New Tab Working!&lt;/title&gt;\n      &lt;/head&gt;\n      &lt;body&gt;\n            &lt;h2&gt;This is a new tab page, and it is working! Awesome, possum!&lt;/h2&gt;\n      &lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;\n[/php]\n\nWe\'re keeping it simple. <strong>really</strong> simple. Now, let\'s get into manifest.json. We will go over JSON a little later on, but for now a rough explanation will have to suffice. JSON (Javascript Object Notation) is essentially a way to create, store, and transmit large arrays of information very efficiently using only Javascript.','Writing Your First Google Chrome Extension','','draft','open','open','','','','','2011-02-19 18:30:02','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://nerdtraining.info/?p=74',0,'post','',0),(85,1,'2012-02-08 18:33:14','2012-02-09 00:33:14','','How to Run a Production Website with Git','In this blog post, I\'m going to teach you how to run a real life website using Git for version control.','trash','open','open','','how-to-run-a-production-website-with-git','','','2012-02-08 18:36:24','2012-02-09 00:36:24','',0,'http://piercemoore.com/blog/2012/02/03/set-up-and-maintain-a-production-web-application-using-git/',0,'post','',0),(86,1,'2011-02-10 20:56:36','2011-02-10 20:56:36','This is an example of a WordPress page, you could edit this to put information about yourself or your site so readers know where you are coming from. You can create as many pages like this one or sub-pages as you like and manage all of your content inside of WordPress.','About','','publish','open','open','','about-2','','','2011-02-10 20:56:36','2011-02-10 20:56:36','',0,'http://nerdtraining.info/?page_id=2',0,'page','',0),(4,1,'2011-02-10 21:36:17','2011-02-10 21:36:17','','Introductory Video to Web Development Series','The first video installment of the Web Development series','inherit','open','open','','introvideo','','','2011-02-10 21:36:17','2011-02-10 21:36:17','',0,'http://piercemoore.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/IntroVideo.avi',0,'attachment','video/avi',0),(6,1,'2011-02-12 00:09:14','2011-02-12 00:09:14','Hello there, viewers! This is the first and introductory video to the NerdTraining PHP series. This video lays out the roadmap of learning for part one of the PHP series covering fundamentals like:\r\n\r\n1) What is PHP?\r\n2) How does PHP work?\r\n3) Variables\r\n4) Data Types\r\n5) Functions\r\n6) Error Handling\r\n7) Overview of Object-Oriented PHP\r\n\r\nThis video series will contain a relatively large number of videos, as will all subsequent video series. Trying to be in depth, ya know? With that, let\'s get started learning PHP!<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/19824589?title=0&amp;byline=0&amp;portrait=0\" width=\"400\" height=\"300\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe><p><a href=\"http://vimeo.com/19824589\">Nerd Training - PHP Edition - Part One - Intro</a> from <a href=\"http://vimeo.com/nerdtraining\">Pierce Moore</a> on <a href=\"http://vimeo.com\">Vimeo</a>.</p>','Introductory video to PHP Edition - Part One','','publish','open','open','','introductory-video-to-php-edition-part-one','','','2012-02-13 22:32:46','2012-02-14 04:32:46','',0,'http://nerdtraining.info/?p=6',0,'post','',0),(105,1,'2011-02-12 00:04:04','2011-02-12 06:04:04','Hey guys, just a quick thing.\n\nI am currently using the Wordpress theme \"Mystique\" for the blog, though this will change as soon as I have time to put together a new theme. Mystique is a great theme, though, you should definitely check it out at <a href=\"http://digitalnature.ro/projects/mystique/\">their home page</a>.\n\nThere is a slight problem that I found, though, and it is one that is pretty common: the Twitter plugin. Try as I might, I just couldn\'t get the theme to load my tweets, instead defaulting back to Wordpress\' tweets on every page load. I left the \"twitter username\" field empty in settings and even dug through the code in <code>widgets.php</code> looking for a solution. Which I eventually found, but not in <code>widgets.php</code>. The solution was actually painfully simple:\n\n<h2><code>Sidebar.php</code></h2>\n\nTurns out, someone hardcoded the \"Wordpress\" username for tweets to be loaded in the feed, instead of even listening to the user\'s input through the settings panel.\n\n<h2>Solution</h2>\n\n[php title=\"Before: Notice the &#039;wordpress&#039; username.\"]the_widget(\'TwitterWidget\', array(\'title\'=&gt;__(\'My latest tweets\',\'mystique\'), \'twituser\'=&gt;\'wordpress\', \'twitcount\'=&gt;\'5\'), array(\'widget_id\'=&gt;\'instance-twitterwidget\',\'before_widget\' =&gt; \'&lt;li class=&quot;block&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;block-twitter&quot;&gt;\',\'after_widget\' =&gt; \'&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\',\'before_title\' =&gt; \'&lt;h3 class=&quot;title&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;\',\'after_title\' =&gt; \'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;block-div&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;block-div-arrow&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\'));[/php]\n\n[php title=\"After: Changing the hardcoded username fixed it right up!\"]the_widget(\'TwitterWidget\', array(\'title\'=&gt;__(\'My latest tweets\',\'mystique\'), \'twituser\'=&gt;\'kiapierce\', \'twitcount\'=&gt;\'5\'), array(\'widget_id\'=&gt;\'instance-twitterwidget\',\'before_widget\' =&gt; \'&lt;li class=&quot;block&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;block-twitter&quot;&gt;\',\'after_widget\' =&gt; \'&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\',\'before_title\' =&gt; \'&lt;h3 class=&quot;title&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;\',\'after_title\' =&gt; \'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;block-div&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;block-div-arrow&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\'));[/php]\n\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\nThis was such a pain in the ass, and the fix being so easy only made it worse. *sigh* Oh well, you live and you learn :)\n\nUntil next time.','Fixing the Twitter Plugin in Mystique','','inherit','open','open','','88-revision','','','2011-02-12 00:04:04','2011-02-12 06:04:04','',88,'http://piercemoore.com/blog/2011/02/12/88-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(13,1,'2011-02-12 04:44:23','2011-02-12 04:44:23','In today\'s video, we will be going over the basics of PHP. What is it? How does it work? Will it bake me cookies? Points include:<!--more-->\r\n\r\nHypertext Pre-Processor\r\nMany, many resources online\r\nPHP.net\r\nTizag.com\r\nW3schools.com\r\nServer-Side Processing\r\nNot Client Side\r\nScripted, *NOT* compiled prog. Language\r\nCompiled at runtime by the PHP interpreter (php.exe)\r\nCompiled software like C++/Java cannot be modified at runtime\r\nVery flexible language, *NOT* strongly typed\r\nNo data types need to be declared\r\nEasy for beginners to pick up\r\nTwo forms\r\nEmbedded in HTML\r\nUnique, individual .php files\r\nInvisible in source code reader\r\nBecause it is compiled on the server, the interpreter only sends to user the final result of the php script.\r\n\r\nSpoiler: No, PHP cannot bake you cookies.\r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/19826394?title=0&amp;byline=0&amp;portrait=0\" width=\"400\" height=\"300\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe><p><a href=\"http://vimeo.com/19826394\">Nerd Training - PHP Edition - Part One - Summary of PHP</a> from <a href=\"http://vimeo.com/nerdtraining\">Pierce Moore</a> on <a href=\"http://vimeo.com\">Vimeo</a>.</p>','Summary of PHP','','publish','open','open','','summary-of-php','','','2012-02-13 22:30:23','2012-02-14 04:30:23','',0,'http://nerdtraining.info/?p=13',0,'post','',0),(104,1,'2011-02-12 00:09:14','2011-02-12 00:09:14','Hello there, viewers! This is the first and introductory video to the NerdTraining PHP series. This video lays out the roadmap of learning for part one of the PHP series covering fundamentals like:\n\n1) What is PHP?\n2) How does PHP work?\n3) Variables\n4) Data Types\n5) Functions\n6) Error Handling\n7) Overview of Object-Oriented PHP\n\nThis video series will contain a relatively large number of videos, as will all subsequent video series. Trying to be in depth, ya know? With that, let\'s get started learning PHP!\n\n<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/19824589\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" frameborder=\"0\"></iframe><p><a href=\"http://vimeo.com/19824589\">Nerd Training - PHP Edition - Part One - Intro</a> from <a href=\"http://vimeo.com/nerdtraining\">Pierce Moore</a> on <a href=\"http://vimeo.com\">Vimeo</a>.</p>','Introductory video to PHP Edition - Part One','','inherit','open','open','','6-revision','','','2011-02-12 00:09:14','2011-02-12 00:09:14','',6,'http://piercemoore.com/blog/2011/02/12/6-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(19,1,'2011-02-12 04:46:20','2011-02-12 04:46:20','In this video, we go over the process of how a web page loads for a user, from the time the URL is typed into the browser till the time the page is rendered on the client side.\r\n\r\nIt\'s automagical!\r\n\r\nSpoiler: It\'s not automagical.<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/19847654?title=0&amp;byline=0&amp;portrait=0\" width=\"400\" height=\"300\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe><p><a href=\"http://vimeo.com/19847654\">Nerd Training - PHP Edition - Part One - How a Web Page Loads</a> from <a href=\"http://vimeo.com/nerdtraining\">Pierce Moore</a> on <a href=\"http://vimeo.com\">Vimeo</a>.</p>','How a Web Page Loads','','publish','open','open','','how-a-web-page-loads','','','2012-02-13 22:31:22','2012-02-14 04:31:22','',0,'http://nerdtraining.info/?p=19',0,'post','',0),(103,1,'2011-02-12 04:44:23','2011-02-12 04:44:23','In today\'s video, we will be going over the basics of PHP. What is it? How does it work? Will it bake me cookies? Points include:\n\nHypertext Pre-Processor\nMany, many resources online\nPHP.net\nTizag.com\nW3schools.com\nServer-Side Processing\nNot Client Side\nScripted, *NOT* compiled prog. Language\nCompiled at runtime by the PHP interpreter (php.exe)\nCompiled software like C++/Java cannot be modified at runtime\nVery flexible language, *NOT* strongly typed\nNo data types need to be declared\nEasy for beginners to pick up\nTwo forms\nEmbedded in HTML\nUnique, individual .php files\nInvisible in source code reader\nBecause it is compiled on the server, the interpreter only sends to user the final result of the php script.\n\nSpoiler: No, PHP cannot bake you cookies.\n\n<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/19826394\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" frameborder=\"0\"></iframe><p><a href=\"http://vimeo.com/19826394\">Nerd Training - PHP Edition - Part One - Summary of PHP</a> from <a href=\"http://vimeo.com/nerdtraining\">Pierce Moore</a> on <a href=