directory \"/home/git/\".\r\n\r\nCreate the new repo and initialize it with the following commands:\r\n<pre>mkdir webapp.git\r\ncd !$\r\ngit init --bare</pre>\r\nNow we have to create the directory that will be the document root of the web application. This will be the directory that will receive the files we push to the server.\r\n<pre>mkdir /var/www/html/webappdocroot/</pre>\r\nNow we need to do one last bit of magic, and this is really the crucial piece of work that makes it all happen. We need to set up our git repo so that it checks out our files to the actual Document Root of the web application whenever it receives a push from a programmer. Run the following commands so that we can make this happen:\r\n<pre>nano hooks/post-receive</pre>\r\nThen, in hooks/post-receive, enter this information. Make sure you change the work tree path to whatever the document root is for your application ( /var/www/html/ ).\r\n\r\n[php]\r\n#!/bin/sh\r\nGIT_WORK_TREE=/var/www/html/webappdocroot/ git checkout -f master\r\n[/php]\r\n\r\nNow, we need to make that file executable by the git user: THIS IS ABSOLUTELY CRUCIAL. Failure to do this will make this all null and void.\r\n<pre>chmod +x hooks/post-receive</pre>\r\nThis should all go well, and you are ALL DONE on the remote server.\r\n<h2>Step Six: Install Git on your LOCAL Computer</h2>\r\nThis is a pretty easy step as well. Even easier for Mac and Linux users. I\'m not going to go step by step, but follow the instructions in the linked tutorials.\r\n\r\nFor Windows users: <a href=\"http://help.github.com/win-set-up-git/\">http://help.github.com/win-set-up-git/</a>\r\n\r\nFor Mac Users: <a href=\"http://help.github.com/mac-set-up-git/\">http://help.github.com/mac-set-up-git/</a>\r\n\r\nFor Linux Users: <a href=\"http://help.github.com/linux-set-up-git/\">http://help.github.com/linux-set-up-git/</a>\r\n<h2>Step Seven: Get Your Files Ready on Your LOCAL Computer</h2>\r\nFor Windows users, you will need to open \"Git Bash\", which should be available in Start &gt; Programs. Mac and Linux users should already have the Git commands available to them in the command line or terminal.  Navigate to the folder where you are keeping your web application or where you will be keeping the documents. If I were to keep them on my desktop in a folder called \"WebApp\", the command would be (on Windows):\r\n<pre>cd C:/Users/Pierce/Desktop/WebApp/</pre>\r\nNow, we need to initialize the git repository in this folder. This is done so that the filesystem can track changes to the files and update the remote server accordingly.\r\n<pre>git init</pre>\r\nYou should get the following success message:\r\n<pre>Initialized empty git repository...</pre>\r\nNow we need to add the remote server as a git repo and get them communicating.\r\n<pre>git remote add web ssh://git@127.0.0.1/home/git/webapp.git</pre>\r\nIf you are running SSH on a different port than the standard port 22 (recommended) the command becomes\r\n<pre>git remote add web ssh://git@127.0.0.1:1234/home/git/webapp.git</pre>\r\nNow, let\'s get our files pushed to the server!\r\n<h2>Step Eight, final step! Push your web application to the server!</h2>\r\nMake sure we\'re still in the local directory that will be the working directory for git. At this point, I\'m assuming that you already have the files for your website in the directory so we are just going to send them all to the web server.\r\n<pre>git add *\r\ngit commit -m \"First commit\"\r\ngit push webapp -all</pre>\r\nAnd bam. There it is. With the success of that push (it should work), you should check your remote server in that directory and you should have all your files in it!\r\n<h1>Recap: What we just did and why.</h1>\r\nWe just set up your webserver and local computer with Git, a powerful versioning system. Now you can live without fear of programming. All you need to do now is work on your code locally (which is faster anyway) and push it to the remote server whenever you are done. If it messes something up? You can just revert to a prior commit! That is the power of Git: endless confidence in yourself, your programming, and the stability of your web application.\r\n\r\nHappy Gitting!\r\n\r\n-Pierce','Set Up and Maintain a Production Web Application Using Git','In this blog post, I\'m going to teach you how to run a real life website using Git for version control.','inherit','open','open','','27-revision-38','','','2012-02-08 18:34:38','2012-02-09 00:34:38','',27,'http://piercemoore.com/blog/2012/02/08/27-revision-38/',0,'revision','',0),(100,1,'2012-02-08 18:33:14','2012-02-09 00:33:14','','How to Run a Production Website with Git','In this blog post, I\'m going to teach you how to run a real life website using Git for version control.','inherit','open','open','','85-revision-2','','','2012-02-08 18:33:14','2012-02-09 00:33:14','',85,'http://piercemoore.com/blog/2012/02/08/85-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(101,1,'2011-02-12 04:45:45','2011-02-12 10:45:45','I am sure that someday I will write a more exhaustive article weighing the pros and cons of making the switch to solid state drives (SSDs), but today I just wanted to share a comparison of the two, having recently made the jump myself.\n\nThe original hard drive running my Windows installation was a 500gb Western Digital green drive, running 5400rpm and spinning to 7200rpm whenever data was required.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_56\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"345\" caption=\"Western Digital 500gb Green Drive\"]<a href=\"http://piercemoore.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/wd500gbDrive.jpg\"><img src=\"http://piercemoore.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/wd500gbDrive.jpg\" alt=\"Western Digital 500gb Green Drive\" title=\"Western Digital 500gb Green Drive\" width=\"345\" height=\"345\" class=\"size-full wp-image-56\" /></a>[/caption]\n\nThe new setup that I just got installed includes two 60gb OC Z Agility 2 solid state drives and a 4 port Syba RAID controller (mucho cheapo, to be honest).\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_54\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"450\" caption=\"OCZ Agility 2 2.5-inch SSD\"]<a href=\"http://piercemoore.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/OCZ-Agility-2-MLC-2.5-inch-SSD.jpg\"><img src=\"http://piercemoore.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/OCZ-Agility-2-MLC-2.5-inch-SSD.jpg\" alt=\"OCZ Agility 2 2.5-inch SSD\" title=\"OCZ Agility 2 2.5-inch SSD\" width=\"450\" height=\"340\" class=\"size-full wp-image-54\" /></a>[/caption]\n[caption id=\"attachment_55\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"616\" caption=\"Syba 4 Port RAID Controller\"]<a href=\"http://piercemoore.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/sybaRaidController.jpg\"><img src=\"http://piercemoore.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/sybaRaidController.jpg\" alt=\"Syba 4 Port RAID Controller\" title=\"Syba 4 Port RAID Controller\" width=\"616\" height=\"436\" class=\"size-full wp-image-55\" /></a>[/caption]\n\nJust for a bit of foundation, the rest of the computer includes an Intel Core2Quad 6600 Processor running 2.4ghz on a Gigabyte motherboard with 4gb of G.Skill RAM.\n\n<h2>The Fun Stuff</h2>\n\nI just took the time to measure the speed of the normal HDD using <a href=\"http://www.hdtune.com/\">HDTune</a>, a hard disk benchmarking application. These were my results:\n[caption id=\"attachment_57\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"570\" caption=\"WD500gb Hard Drive Benchmark\"]<a href=\"http://piercemoore.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/HDTune_Benchmark_WDC_WD5000AACS-00ZUB0.png\"><img src=\"http://piercemoore.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/HDTune_Benchmark_WDC_WD5000AACS-00ZUB0.png\" alt=\"WD500gb Hard Drive Benchmark\" title=\"WD500gb Hard Drive Benchmark\" width=\"570\" height=\"460\" class=\"size-full wp-image-57\" /></a>[/caption]\n\nNot horrible, but pretty much exactly what we have come to expect from a platter-based hard drive. Definitely not good, just acceptable. What we have come to expect.\n<h3>Pertinent Data from HDD Test</a></h3>\nAverage Read Rate: 60mb/s (Not too shabby)\nAverage Seek/Access time: 14ms (Shabby)\nObservation: As strain is continuously placed on the hard drive, the read rates drop and the access times go up.\n\n<br />\n\nNow, let\'s take a look at how nice dual SSDs in RAID 0 changed the game:\n[caption id=\"attachment_58\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"570\" caption=\"120gb Dual SSD RAID 0 Benchmark\"]<a href=\"http://piercemoore.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/HDTune_Benchmark_LovestickSr.png\"><img src=\"http://piercemoore.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/HDTune_Benchmark_LovestickSr.png\" alt=\"120gb Dual SSD RAID 0 Benchmark\" title=\"120gb Dual SSD RAID 0 Benchmark\" width=\"570\" height=\"460\" class=\"size-full wp-image-58\" /></a>[/caption]\n\nWow. I know right? It\'s okay, you don\'t need to say anything.\n\n<h3>Pertinent Data from SSD Test</h3>\nAverage Read Rate: 154.4mb/s\nAccess Times: <strong>0.2ms</strong> (Yes, you read that correctly. 0.2ms!)\nObservation: Even during extended strain on the disk, the disk\'s read rate never drops more than 1mb/s total, in fact gets even faster as time goes on.\n\n<h2>What This Means</h2>\n<ol>\n	<li>As tested, the Dual SSD RAID 0 setup increased disk read rate by almost 3 times.</li>\n	<li>As tested, the setup decreased data access times to <strong>1/73</strong> of their original values.</li>\n	<li>Solid state technology does not suffer from the negative effects of moving parts, and consequently is not affected by extended strain.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\nThere\'s really not any other way to say it: SSD is the way to go. And if you have $300? Get two and throw \'em in a RAID controller. Who knows? If you spend more than $30 on a RAID controller, you could likely increase your disk read rate to as much as 400mb/s.\n\n<br /><br />\nThat\'s all for now. Y\'all take it easy!\n-Pierce','The Benefits of SSDs over Normal HDDs','','inherit','open','open','','96-revision','','','2011-02-12 04:45:45','2011-02-12 10:45:45','',96,'http://piercemoore.com/blog/2011/02/12/96-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(102,1,'2011-02-12 04:46:20','2011-02-12 04:46:20','In this video, we go over the process of how a web page loads for a user, from the time the URL is typed into the browser till the time the page is rendered on the client side.\n\nIt\'s automagical!\n\nSpoiler: It\'s not automagical.\n\n<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/19847654\" width=\"600\" height=\"450\" frameborder=\"0\"></iframe><p><a href=\"http://vimeo.com/19847654\">Nerd Training - PHP Edition - Part One - How a Web Page Loads</a> from <a href=\"http://vimeo.com/nerdtraining\">Pierce Moore</a> on <a href=\"http://vimeo.com\">Vimeo</a>.</p>','How a Web Page Loads','','inherit','open','open','','19-revision','','','2011-02-12 04:46:20','2011-02-12 04:46:20','',19,'http://piercemoore.com/blog/2011/02/12/19-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(106,1,'2012-02-08 18:39:24','2012-02-09 00:39:24','Hey guys, just a quick thing.\n\nI am currently using the Wordpress theme \"Mystique\" for the blog, though this will change as soon as I have time to put together a new theme. Mystique is a great theme, though, you should definitely check it out at <a href=\"http://digitalnature.ro/projects/mystique/\">their home page</a>.<!--more-->\n\nThere is a slight problem that I found, though, and it is one that is pretty common: the Twitter plugin. Try as I might, I just couldn\'t get the theme to load my tweets, instead defaulting back to Wordpress\' tweets on every page load. I left the \"twitter username\" field empty in settings and even dug through the code in <code>widgets.php</code> looking for a solution. Which I eventually found, but not in <code>widgets.php</code>. The solution was actually painfully simple:\n<h2><code>Sidebar.php</code></h2>\nTurns out, someone hardcoded the \"Wordpress\" username for tweets to be loaded in the feed, instead of even listening to the user\'s input through the settings panel.\n<h2>Solution</h2>\n[php title=\"Before: Notice the &#039;wordpress&#039; username.\"]the_widget(\'TwitterWidget\', array(\'title\'=&gt;__(\'My latest tweets\',\'mystique\'), \'twituser\'=&gt;\'wordpress\', \'twitcount\'=&gt;\'5\'), array(\'widget_id\'=&gt;\'instance-twitterwidget\',\'before_widget\' =&gt; \'&lt;li class=&quot;block&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;block-twitter&quot;&gt;\',\'after_widget\' =&gt; \'&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\',\'before_title\' =&gt; \'&lt;h3 class=&quot;title&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;\',\'after_title\' =&gt; \'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;block-div&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;block-div-arrow&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\'));[/php]\n\n[php title=\"After: Changing the hardcoded username fixed it right up!\"]the_widget(\'TwitterWidget\', array(\'title\'=&gt;__(\'My latest tweets\',\'mystique\'), \'twituser\'=&gt;\'kiapierce\', \'twitcount\'=&gt;\'5\'), array(\'widget_id\'=&gt;\'instance-twitterwidget\',\'before_widget\' =&gt; \'&lt;li class=&quot;block&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;block-twitter&quot;&gt;\',\'after_widget\' =&gt; \'&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\',\'before_title\' =&gt; \'&lt;h3 class=&quot;title&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;\',\'after_title\' =&gt; \'&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;block-div&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;block-div-arrow&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\'));[/php]\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\nThis was such a pain in the ass, and the fix being so easy only made it worse. *sigh* Oh well, you live and you learn :)\n\nUntil next time.','Fixing the Twitter Plugin in Mystique','','inherit','open','open','','88-autosave','','','2012-02-08 18:39:24','2012-02-09 00:39:24','',88,'http://piercemoore.com/blog/2012/02/08/88-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(107,1,'2012-02-13 22:30:09','2012-02-14 04:30:09','In today\'s video, we will be going over the basics of PHP. What is it? How does it work? Will it bake me cookies? Points include:<!--more-->\n\nHypertext Pre-Processor\nMany, many resources online\nPHP.net\nTizag.com\nW3schools.com\nServer-Side Processing\nNot Client S